# EF Core Write-Side and Hot-Path Tuning

## How SaveChanges actually works

Change tracker diffs snapshots → generates INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE **batched** into few round-trips (default max ~42 statements/batch, configurable via `MaxBatchSize`) → wraps them in **one implicit transaction**. You rarely need `BeginTransaction` for a single SaveChanges.

## The row-at-a-time trap

```csharp
// ❌ loads 50k entities into memory, tracks them, updates one by one
var stale = await db.Products.Where(p => p.DiscontinuedAt < cutoff).ToListAsync();
foreach (var p in stale) p.IsActive = false;
await db.SaveChangesAsync();

// ✅ EF7+: one UPDATE statement, no loading, no tracking
await db.Products.Where(p => p.DiscontinuedAt < cutoff)
    .ExecuteUpdateAsync(s => s.SetProperty(p => p.IsActive, false));

await db.Products.Where(p => p.IsOrphaned).ExecuteDeleteAsync();
```

`ExecuteUpdate`/`ExecuteDelete` bypass the change tracker entirely — set-based SQL, exactly what the database wants. Caveats: no concurrency tokens, no domain events from tracked entities — use consciously.

True bulk inserts (100k+ rows): `SqlBulkCopy` (or EFCore.BulkExtensions) — orders of magnitude over Add+SaveChanges.

## Change tracker hygiene on big imports

Long-lived context accumulating 100k tracked entities = quadratic slowdown. Batch: SaveChanges every ~1-5k, then `db.ChangeTracker.Clear()`, or new context per batch.

## Compiled queries for ultra-hot paths

```csharp
private static readonly Func<AppDbContext, int, Task<Product?>> GetProduct =
    EF.CompileAsyncQuery((AppDbContext db, int id) =>
        db.Products.FirstOrDefault(p => p.Id == id));
```

Skips LINQ-to-SQL translation per call (~10-30% on trivial queries called thousands/sec). Measure first; it's a micro-optimization with maintenance cost.

## Connection resiliency

```csharp
options.UseSqlServer(cs, o => o.EnableRetryOnFailure());
```

Retries transient connection faults (Azure SQL failovers). Note: with explicit BeginTransaction you must wrap the whole unit in `CreateExecutionStrategy().ExecuteAsync(...)`.

# Set-Based Thinking

The #1 mindset gap between app developers and database engines: apps think **row by row** (RBAR — Row By Agonizing Row); SQL engines are optimized for **sets**.

## The everyday crimes

```csharp
// ❌ 500 round-trips
foreach (var id in productIds)
    results.Add(await db.Products.FirstOrDefaultAsync(p => p.Id == id));

// ✅ one query
var results = await db.Products.Where(p => productIds.Contains(p.Id)).ToListAsync();
```

`Contains` translates to `IN (...)` — good to a few hundred values. Thousands of values = giant SQL text, plan cache pollution (every count = different query), and an 8k-parameter limit. Enter TVPs:

## Table-Valued Parameters

```sql
CREATE TYPE dbo.IntList AS TABLE (Id INT PRIMARY KEY);
```

```csharp
var table = new DataTable();
table.Columns.Add("Id", typeof(int));
foreach (var id in ids) table.Rows.Add(id);

var p = new SqlParameter("@ids", SqlDbType.Structured)
{ TypeName = "dbo.IntList", Value = table };

var products = await db.Products
    .FromSqlRaw("SELECT p.* FROM Products p JOIN @ids i ON i.Id = p.Id", p)
    .ToListAsync();
```

One parameterized round-trip, real JOIN semantics, one cached plan regardless of list size, 10k+ ids no problem. Also ideal for **bulk upserts**: pass a TVP of rows to a proc doing `MERGE`/`UPDATE+INSERT`.

## The general rewrite discipline

| RBAR pattern | Set-based fix |
|---|---|
| Loop of SELECT by id | `IN` / TVP JOIN |
| Loop of UPDATE per row | one UPDATE with JOIN / `ExecuteUpdateAsync` |
| Loop INSERT | batched SaveChanges / SqlBulkCopy / TVP |
| Cursor in T-SQL computing running totals | window functions (`SUM() OVER`) |

Rule of thumb: **if there's a database call inside a foreach, stop and redesign.** The database can almost always do the whole set in one statement — and the round-trip latency you save often dwarfs every index tweak in this course.
